        rdfs:comment        "CD28 signaling plays a critical role in shaping immune responses by ensuring effective T-cell activation and enhancing T-cell survival and proliferation. When CD28 engages its ligands, B7-1 (CD80) and B7-2 (CD86), on antigen-presenting cells, it provides an essential secondary signal that complements T-cell receptor (TCR) activation. This costimulatory signal leads to the production of interleukin-2 (IL-2), which supports the clonal expansion of T cells, promoting both their proliferation and survival by initiating anti-apoptotic pathways (Ribot et al. 2012, Alegre et al. 2001). <br><br>The cytoplasmic tail of CD28, upon ligand binding, undergoes phosphorylation by Src family kinases like LCK and FYN, triggering downstream signaling pathways involving PI3K, VAV-1, Tec family kinases, AKT, and other adaptor proteins (Sharpe & Freeman 2002; Chen & Flies 2013)." ;
        rdfs:label          "CD28 co-stimulation" ;
        dc:contributor      "Authored: Garapati, Phani Vijay, 2024-11-07" , "Reviewed: Bluestone, JA, Esensten, J, 2009-06-01 18:47:33" , "Edited: Tiwari, Krishna, 2024-11-07" , "Authored: Garapati, P V, 2008-12-16 11:12:19" , "Reviewed: D'Eustachio, Peter, 2024-11-07" , "GOC:reactome_curators" , "Edited: Garapati, P V, 2008-12-16 11:12:19" ;
        dc:date             "2026-06-29" ;
        pav:providedBy      "https://reactome.org" ;
        oboInOwl:hasDbXref  "R-HSA-389356" ;
        skos:narrower       <http://model.geneontology.org/R-HSA-388841/R-HSA-388841> ;
        skos:note           "org.biopax.paxtools.model.level3.Pathway" .

